TITLE: Using BPF_KSYSCALL to Trace 'write' Syscall in C (eBPF)
DESCRIPTION: This C code demonstrates using the `BPF_KSYSCALL` macro within an eBPF program to trace the `write` syscall. The `SEC("ksyscall/write")` directive attaches the program to the syscall entry. `BPF_KSYSCALL` defines the function `bpf_prog3` and automatically provides the syscall arguments (`fd`, `buf`, `count`) typed correctly, abstracting away the need to manually read registers using `PT_REGS_*` macros. The program calculates a histogram key based on process/user info and the logarithm of the write size, then updates a count in the `my_hist_map` eBPF map. It relies on libbpf helper functions like `bpf_map_lookup_elem`, `bpf_map_update_elem`, and functions to get current process/user context.
SOURCE: https://github.com/isovalent/ebpf-docs/blob/master/docs/ebpf-library/libbpf/ebpf/BPF_KSYSCALL.md#2025-04-22_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: c
CODE:
```
SEC("ksyscall/write")
int BPF_KSYSCALL(bpf_prog3, unsigned int fd, const char *buf, size_t count)
{
\tlong init_val = 1;
\tlong *value;
\tstruct hist_key key;

\tkey.index = log2l(count);
\tkey.pid_tgid = bpf_get_current_pid_tgid();
\tkey.uid_gid = bpf_get_current_uid_gid();
\tbpf_get_current_comm(&key.comm, sizeof(key.comm));

\tvalue = bpf_map_lookup_elem(&my_hist_map, &key);
\tif (value)
\t\t__sync_fetch_and_add(value, 1);
\telse
\t\tbpf_map_update_elem(&my_hist_map, &key, &init_val, BPF_ANY);
\treturn 0;
}
```

